---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import Hero from "../../components/Hero.astro";
import SectionIntro from "../../components/SectionIntro.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Proxmox Cluster Security Lab | GabrielsMind"
  description="A segmented Proxmox cluster built to support SOC workflows, hostile-zone testing, security research isolation, and realistic cyber lab operations."
>
  <Hero
    eyebrow="Proxmox · Segmentation · Security Lab · Infrastructure"
    title="A Proxmox cluster built as security infrastructure, not just virtualization."
    text="This project is a multi-node security lab designed to support SOC workflows, adversary simulation, isolated research zones, and controlled cyber experimentation. The design focus was not only compute — it was segmentation, containment, and operational realism."
    primaryHref="/reports/"
    primaryLabel="Read Research"
    secondaryHref="/contact/"
    secondaryLabel="Contact Me"
    imageSrc="/images/about-reflection.jpg"
    imageAlt="Gabriel working with a laptop in an urban setting"
  />

  <section class="intro-strip">
    <div class="container intro-strip-inner">
      <div>
        <span class="intro-label">Core goal</span>
        <p>Build a flexible virtualized lab that supports both security operations and adversary testing without collapsing into one flat network.</p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <span class="intro-label">Engineering focus</span>
        <p>Segmentation, node roles, isolated zones, firewall control, and infrastructure that supports realistic technical scenarios.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <SectionIntro
      eyebrow="Overview"
      title="Why this project exists"
      text="Many labs fail because they are built as collections of tools instead of systems. This cluster was designed as a foundation for multiple security use cases."
    />

    <div class="grid grid-2">
      <article class="card">
        <h3>Problem</h3>
        <p class="muted">
          A useful cyber lab needs more than virtualization. It needs isolation boundaries, realistic network paths, role separation, and room for both offensive and defensive workflows.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h3>Approach</h3>
        <p class="muted">
          Build a Proxmox-based cluster with segmented zones, security-aware node usage, and supporting infrastructure that can host SOC tooling, hostile networks, controlled victim systems, and research workloads.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <SectionIntro
      eyebrow="Architecture"
      title="What the environment is designed to support"
      text="The cluster is intended to support multiple parallel use cases without turning the lab into one insecure flat environment."
    />

    <div class="grid grid-3">
      <article class="card">
        <h3>SOC operations</h3>
        <p class="muted">Security monitoring, log ingestion, enrichment, triage, and detection workflow testing.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <h3>Hostile-zone testing</h3>
        <p class="muted">Controlled attacker-to-victim paths, malware research isolation, and adversary simulation with containment in mind.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <h3>Infrastructure experimentation</h3>
        <p class="muted">Virtual networking, firewall policies, service placement, and secure remote access design.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <SectionIntro
      eyebrow="Security design"
      title="Engineering choices that matter"
      text="These are the decisions that make the project worth showing, because they demonstrate technical judgment rather than just installation effort."
    />

    <div class="grid grid-2">
      <article class="card">
        <h3>Segmentation first</h3>
        <p class="muted">
          Zones are separated intentionally instead of sharing a flat lab network. This reduces risk, makes attack paths clearer, and improves realism for both offensive and defensive scenarios.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h3>Role-driven infrastructure</h3>
        <p class="muted">
          Compute resources, nodes, and services are placed based on function. That makes the lab easier to operate, scale, troubleshoot, and explain.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h3>Firewall and boundary control</h3>
        <p class="muted">
          The environment is built with security boundaries in mind, using firewall logic and controlled pathways between networks rather than unrestricted east-west movement.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="card">
        <h3>Built for realistic workflows</h3>
        <p class="muted">
          The goal is not just spinning up VMs. The goal is supporting detection engineering, incident response, hostile testing, and research under realistic constraints.
        </p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <SectionIntro
      eyebrow="What I learned"
      title="Technical lessons from the project"
      text="The strongest infrastructure projects are not just builds. They are opportunities to learn where architecture, usability, and security friction actually appear."
    />

    <div class="card">
      <ul class="learn-list">
        <li>Segmentation decisions become much easier when the use cases are defined first.</li>
        <li>Cluster design needs operational clarity, not just hardware availability.</li>
        <li>Security labs gain value when they support both detection and adversary perspectives.</li>
        <li>Infrastructure projects become stronger when they are documented as systems, not screenshots.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

  <style>
    .intro-strip {
      position: relative;
      margin-top: -2rem;
      z-index: 3;
    }

    .intro-strip-inner {
      display: grid;
      grid-template-columns: repeat(2, minmax(0, 1fr));
      gap: 1rem;
      padding: 1rem;
      border-radius: 22px;
      background: rgba(8, 14, 28, 0.62);
      border: 1px solid rgba(255, 255, 255, 0.08);
      backdrop-filter: blur(14px);
      box-shadow: 0 20px 50px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.24);
    }

    .intro-label {
      display: inline-block;
      margin-bottom: 0.45rem;
      color: var(--accent);
      font-size: 0.78rem;
      font-weight: 700;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      letter-spacing: 0.08em;
    }

    .intro-strip p {
      margin: 0;
      color: var(--muted);
    }

    .learn-list {
      margin: 0;
      padding-left: 1.25rem;
      color: var(--muted);
    }

    .learn-list li + li {
      margin-top: 0.8rem;
    }

    @media (max-width: 900px) {
      .intro-strip-inner {
        grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      }

      .intro-strip {
        margin-top: -1rem;
      }
    }
  </style>
</BaseLayout>
